description: From Middle English midwif, corresponding to mid (“with”) + wif (“woman, wife, female”). It appears not to be entirely clear whether the original understanding was “with-woman” in the sense of “attending/assisting woman”, or “they who are with the woman” (namely the mother).

entries.meaning: A person, usually a woman, who is trained to assist women in childbirth, but who is not a physician.
examples: A hundred years ago, a midwife would bring the baby into the world - going to a hospital to deliver a baby was either impossible or unheard of.

entries.meaning: (rare, figuratively) Someone who assists in bringing about some result or project.

verbs.description: midwife (third-person singular simple present midwifes, present participle midwifing, simple past and past participle midwifed)

entries.meaning: (transitive, figuratively) To facilitate the emergence of.
examples: But the bigger objective was to help Iraqis midwife a democratic model that could inspire reform across the Arab-Muslim world and give the youth there a chance at a better future.
